<h3 id="sass-utilities">Sass utilities</h3>
<p>The <code>breakpoint()</code> Sass function can be used to get the value of a breakpoint directly. However, breakpoints are generally more useful as <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/Media_Queries/Using_media_queries">media queries</a>, for which there are the <code>breakpoint-above()</code> and <code>breakpoint-below()</code> mixins. Example:</p>
<pre><code class="language-css">@include breakpoint-above(&quot;small&quot;) {
  // Applies only to screen sizes above 640px.
}

@include breakpoint-below(&quot;large&quot;) {
  // Applies only to screen sizes below 1024px.
}
</code></pre>
<p>Because the majority of visitors are on handheld devices, <strong>we recommend a &quot;mobile-first&quot; approach to responsive strategy.</strong> Therefore, the <code>breakpoint-above()</code> mixin is recommended for most cases, <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/Progressive_Enhancement" title="Progressive Enhancement - MDN Web Docs Glossary">progressively enhancing</a> designs as the screen gets wider. The older approach is &quot;desktop-first&quot;, <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/Graceful_degradation" title="Graceful degradation - MDN Web Docs Glossary">gracefully degrading</a> a design as the screen gets smaller, which can still be done if necessary with the <code>breakpoint-below()</code> mixin.</p>
<p><strong>Use custom breakpoints.</strong> The provided breakpoints are only reasonable defaults, not hard-set rules. Consider using custom breakpoints to optimize for the specific experience at hand. For custom breakpoints, standard CSS <code>@media</code> query syntax can be used, or a custom value can be passed to the mixins:</p>
<pre><code class="language-css">@include breakpoint-above(&quot;123px&quot;) {
  // Custom breakpoint.
}
</code></pre>
